      "content": "Sure thing! Here are the actual steps to fix your dripping compression faucet, with a quick goblin‑flavoring sprinkled in just for fun.\n\n1. **Turn off the water supply**  \n   Locate the shut‑off valve under the sink (or the main water line) and turn it off. If you’re not sure where it is, look for a small valve near the base of the faucet—goblins often hide near water sources, so you’ll be in good company.\n\n2. **Remove the faucet handle**  \n   Use the adjustable wrench to loosen the nut that holds the handle. Tighten it just enough to pull the handle off. A loose handle means you can see the internal valve better.\n\n3. **Extract the old washer**  \n   With the pipe wrench, tighten the compression nut. This will pull out the old washer. Be careful not to over‑tighten, or you might crack the faucet body.\n\n4. **Install the new washer**  \n   Place the new washer on the valve seat, then tighten the nut back in. Tighten snugly, but not too tight—just enough to seal the seal. If you want, wrap the threads with plumber’s tape for",
